    <string-array name="theory_topic_descriptions">
        <item>Trigonometry studies the relationships between the sides and angles of triangles. The main functions are sine, cosine, and tangent.</item>
        <item>The unit circle is a circle with a radius of 1 centered at the origin. It allows for the visualization of trigonometric functions.</item>
        <item>The sine of an angle α is the y-coordinate of a point on the unit circle. sin(α) = y-coordinate of the point.</item>
        <item>The cosine of an angle α is the x-coordinate of a point on the unit circle. cos(α) = x-coordinate of the point.</item>
        <item>The tangent of an angle α is the ratio of the sine to the cosine. tan(α) = sin(α)/cos(α).</item>
        <item>The cotangent of an angle α is the ratio of the cosine to the sine. cot(α) = cos(α)/sin(α) = 1/tan(α).</item>
        <item>Inverse functions: arcsin, arccos, arctan allow you to find the angle from the value of a trigonometric function.</item>
        <item>Basic identities: sin²α + cos²α = 1, tan α = sin α / cos α, and other important relationships.</item>
    </string-array>

